---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<style lang="scss">
@use '../../../assets/css/_theme.scss' as *;

.alert-box {
	background: $secondary;
	border-left: 3px solid $earth-warm;
	padding: 16px 24px;
	margin: 24px 0;

	p {
		margin: 0;
		font-size: 0.95rem;
	}
}
</style>
<Layout title="Italian Wall Lizards" description="Erell Institute research on invasive Italian wall lizards (Podarcis siculus) in Douglas County, Kansas — a community science project.">
	<main class="page-main">
		<div class="pure-g center">
			<div class="pure-u-1 pure-u-md-4-5 pure-u-lg-3-5 pure-u-xxl-1-2">
				<header class="page-header">
					<h1>Italian Wall Lizards</h1>
					<p class="page-header__lead">
						Community science research on invasive <em>Podarcis siculus</em> in Douglas County, Kansas.
					</p>
				</header>

				<p>
					The Italian wall lizard (<em>Podarcis siculus</em>) is an invasive species with large
					populations established in Topeka and Lawrence, Kansas — as well as New York City,
					Philadelphia, and Los Angeles. This project originated as a community science effort
					during COVID-19, organized through the KU SEEDS Ecology Club and sponsored by Erell Institute.
				</p>

				<p>
					The research is conducted by a team of undergraduate women, sponsored by Doug and Maria Eifler.
					The focus is on understanding how this species thrives where it has been introduced,
					and what that means for native wildlife.
				</p>

				<h2 class="section-title">Research Focus Areas</h2>
				<ul>
					<li>Habitat preferences (Friestad et al. 2023)</li>
					<li>Behavioral syndromes of successful invaders</li>
					<li>Relationship between wall lizards and native skinks</li>
				</ul>

				<h2 class="section-title">Why This Matters</h2>
				<p>
					Invasive wall lizards can outcompete native lizard species, posing a threat to local
					biodiversity. Understanding their habitat preferences and behavioral strategies is the
					first step toward effective management.
				</p>

				<div class="alert-box">
					<p>
						<strong>Important:</strong> If you encounter Italian wall lizards, please do not
						touch or transport them. Contact us at
						<a href="mailto:info@erell.ngo">info@erell.ngo</a> with sightings.
					</p>
				</div>

				<p>
					Questions about this project? Reach the Italian Wall Lizard Task Force at
					<a href="mailto:info@erell.ngo">info@erell.ngo</a>.
				</p>
			</div>
		</div>
	</main>
</Layout>
